            "abstractNote": "Populations of Marianas fruit bats, Pteropus mariannus, were surveyed on each of the 15 Mariana Islands in 1983-1984. It is estimated that a minimum of 8, 700-9,000 fruit bats occur in the archipelago, with about 82-85% of these bats found on the nine northernmost and largely uninhabited islands. The islands of Anatahan, Pagan, and Agrihan had the largest populations, with minimum population estimates Of 3,000, 2,500, and 1,000 bats, respectively. Smaller populations of about 400-1,000 fruit bats occurred on Asuncion, Guguan, Rota, and Guam. The remaining islands in the archipelago were each estimated to have fewer than 125 bats. Population densities of fruit bats were highest on islands with little hunting but were generally much lower on human-inhabited islands where hunting was common.",
